<h1>Phenytoin &amp; Fosphenytoin: The ICU Nurse's Guide</h1>
<p class="hub-crumb" style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:0.9em;background:#f0f4ff;border-left:4px solid #3b6cf8;padding:8px 14px;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;margin:14px 0;">Part of the <a href="icu-emergencies-hub-2026.html"><strong>ICU Emergencies Hub</strong></a> &mdash; browse every related guide in one place.</p>
<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">Phenytoin is one of the oldest second-line agents for status epilepticus, and almost every risk it carries is tied to <em>how</em> you give it &mdash; the rate, the line, the fluid, and the level. Fosphenytoin, its water-soluble prodrug, exists largely to make that administration safer. Here is what a nurse hanging either one needs to have cold.</p>

<div class="hero-note">
<strong>The short version:</strong> Both are used to stop and prevent seizures after benzodiazepines fail. The load is about <strong>20 mg/kg</strong> (phenytoin) or <strong>20 mg PE/kg</strong> (fosphenytoin, dosed in phenytoin-equivalents). <strong>Phenytoin goes no faster than 50 mg/min</strong> with continuous cardiac monitoring; fosphenytoin can run up to 150 mg PE/min. Phenytoin is compatible with <strong>normal saline only</strong> (it precipitates in dextrose). Watch for hypotension and bradyarrhythmia during the load, <strong>purple glove syndrome</strong> at the IV site, and interpret levels against the albumin.</p>
</div>

<h2>Where they fit in status epilepticus</h2>
<p>The treatment ladder is benzodiazepine first, then a second-line agent, then anesthesia. Phenytoin/fosphenytoin has long been a standard second-line choice alongside <a href="levetiracetam-keppra-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">levetiracetam</a> and <a href="valproate-depacon-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">valproate</a>; large trials found the three roughly comparable, so the choice often comes down to interactions, hemodynamics, and what the patient is already on. When these fail, the patient moves to a continuous anesthetic infusion such as <a href="propofol-guide-for-icu-nurses-2026.html">propofol</a> or a barbiturate. See the <a href="phenobarbital-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">phenobarbital</a> guide for the barbiturate end of the ladder.</p>

<h2>Phenytoin vs. fosphenytoin: why the prodrug exists</h2>
<p>IV phenytoin is dissolved in propylene glycol at a highly alkaline pH. That vehicle is what drives the two signature hazards: cardiovascular depression when infused quickly, and severe tissue injury if it extravasates. Fosphenytoin is a water-soluble prodrug that the body rapidly converts to phenytoin, so it can be given faster, hurts far less at the site, and can even be given IM in a pinch. It is dosed in <strong>phenytoin equivalents (PE)</strong> precisely so the numbers match &mdash; 1 mg PE of fosphenytoin yields 1 mg of phenytoin.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Phenytoin</th><th>Fosphenytoin</th></tr>
<tr><td>Max infusion rate</td><td>50 mg/min</td><td>150 mg PE/min</td></tr>
<tr><td>IV site injury</td><td>High (purple glove)</td><td>Much lower</td></tr>
<tr><td>IM route</td><td>No (erratic, painful)</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>Compatible fluid</td><td>Normal saline only</td><td>Saline or dextrose</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cost</td><td>Low</td><td>Higher</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>The rate-and-rhythm rule</h2>
<div class="warning">
<strong>Never push phenytoin faster than 50 mg/min, and keep the patient on continuous cardiac and blood-pressure monitoring during any load.</strong> Rapid infusion causes hypotension, bradycardia, and conduction block &mdash; effects driven largely by the propylene glycol vehicle and the drug's sodium-channel activity. In older or hemodynamically fragile patients, many clinicians slow the rate further. Fosphenytoin's faster ceiling reflects its friendlier vehicle, but it still warrants monitoring because it becomes phenytoin.</div>

<h2>Purple glove syndrome and the line</h2>
<p><strong>Purple glove syndrome</strong> is progressive limb discoloration, edema, and pain that can appear during or after IV phenytoin, even without obvious extravasation, and can progress to serious soft-tissue and vascular injury. Use a large, well-placed IV, avoid small hand veins when possible, flush with saline before and after, and inspect the site frequently. Any dusky discoloration or disproportionate pain means stop and escalate. This risk is one of the strongest arguments for fosphenytoin when IV access is marginal.</p>

<h2>Levels, albumin, and zero-order kinetics</h2>
<p>Phenytoin is highly protein-bound, so the <strong>total level can mislead you</strong> in critically ill patients with low albumin: the total looks "low" while the pharmacologically active free fraction is actually adequate or high. Correct the total level for albumin (the Sheiner-Tozer equation) or, better, measure a <strong>free phenytoin level</strong> when available. Typical targets are roughly a total of 10&ndash;20 mcg/mL or a free level of 1&ndash;2 mcg/mL.</p>
<p>Phenytoin also follows <strong>saturable (zero-order) kinetics</strong> near therapeutic concentrations, so a small dose increase can produce a disproportionate jump in level and tip a patient into toxicity &mdash; nystagmus, ataxia, slurred speech, and lethargy. That non-linear behavior is why levels are followed carefully and why dose changes are made cautiously.</p>

<h2>Compatibility and interactions</h2>
<p>Phenytoin precipitates in dextrose-containing fluids, so it runs in <strong>normal saline only</strong>, ideally through a dedicated line or with a saline flush bracketing the dose. It is also a potent hepatic enzyme inducer with a long list of interactions &mdash; it can lower levels of many co-administered drugs, and its own level is affected by others. On a busy ICU medication list this is a frequent source of hidden problems, so it is worth flagging to pharmacy.</p>

<h2>Why CRNA students should know it</h2>
<p>On the <a href="how-to-become-a-crna-2026.html">CRNA path</a>, phenytoin is a case study in how the vehicle and kinetics &mdash; not just the molecule &mdash; define a drug's danger. The 50 mg/min limit, the saline-only rule, purple glove syndrome, and albumin-corrected levels are classic exam and safety points that also translate directly to the anesthesia and neuro-critical-care settings you will rotate through.</p>

<h2>Bottom line</h2>
<p>Phenytoin and fosphenytoin stop seizures the benzodiazepines could not, but they punish sloppy administration. Load around 20 mg/kg (or PE/kg), hold phenytoin to 50 mg/min on the monitor, run it in saline through a good line, watch the limb for purple glove, and read the level against the albumin. When access is marginal or speed matters, fosphenytoin buys you a wider safety margin.</p>

